1.¶

Please discuss the tension between bias and variance during developing a machine learning model. What is the difference between them and what is the trade-off? How would you classify decision trees and linear regression regarding their level of bias.

Answer¶

  • High Bias suggest training data have less affects on target data so its make less assumptions about target data.

  • High Variance suggest training data is very influential on target data so its make too many assumptions about target data.

  • We can divide prediction error tree which are

    • Bias Error
    • Variance Error
    • Irreducible Error

We can not reduce irreducible error. Our goal is reduce total of Bias Error and Variance Error.

  • For try to minimize Bias Error + Variance Error. We can use;
    • Cross Validation
    • Early Stopping
    • Pruning
    • Regularization

VotingClassifier and Deciding to which algorithm we choose¶

In [354]:
from sklearn.ensemble import VotingClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
In [355]:
clf1 = LogisticRegression(random_state=1)
clf2 = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1)
clf3 = GaussianNB()
clf4 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 7)
clf5 = AdaBoostClassifier()
clf6 = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=110, learning_rate=0.1,
    max_depth=1, random_state=1)
eclf = VotingClassifier(estimators=[('lr', clf1), ('rf', clf2), ('gnb', clf3), 
                                    ('neig',clf4),('ada',clf5),
                                    ('grad',clf6)], voting='hard')

for clf, label in zip([clf1, clf2, clf3, clf4, clf5, clf6, eclf], 
                      ['Logistic Regression', 'Random Forest', 'naive Bayes', 'KNeighbors',
                       'Ada', 'Gradient', 'VotingClassifier']):
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, iris_X, iris_y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    print("Accuracy: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f) [%s]" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), label))

Accuracy: 0.95 (+/- 0.03) [Logistic Regression]
Accuracy: 0.95 (+/- 0.03) [Random Forest]
Accuracy: 0.95 (+/- 0.03) [naive Bayes]
Accuracy: 0.98 (+/- 0.03) [KNeighbors]
Accuracy: 0.93 (+/- 0.03) [Ada]
Accuracy: 0.95 (+/- 0.02) [Gradient]
Accuracy: 0.95 (+/- 0.03) [VotingClassifier]

Result¶

Based on Accuracy mean and sd, I choose KNeighbors method.

6.¶

What’s the difference between Type I and Type II error? Explain your results with the outputs you obtained in the previous questions? (Hint: These errors are also known as false positive/negative).

Answer¶

Type 1 error: reject true hypothesis so hypothesis actually true but we predict it false. Type 2 error: accept false hypothesis so hypothesis actually false but we predict it true.

What are ensemble methods? What are they crucial and widely used? Provide a concrete example where ensemble techniques might be useful.

  • Ramdom Forest
  • AdaBoost
  • Gradient Tree Boosting
  • Voting Classifier are some of ensemble classifying methods.

Ensembling methohs are combine two or more algorithm like one. So predictions results based on more than one algorithms.

its advantages

  • improving accuracy,
  • more robust and stable performances

disadvantages

  • reduce model interpretability
  • time consuming

We have already mentioned that it is important to have a balanced dataset for developing a good model. How would you handle an imbalanced dataset?

Answer¶

  • Collect more data
  • Try to generate new data (Example: we can try to generate random new data from our minority class data set)
  • We can use sensitivity, specifity or (sensitivity*specifity) rather than accuracy. (Try to be creative)

9.¶

What is overfitting? How do you ensure you’re not overfitting with a model? (Hint: You can get help from this link: https://www.quora.com/How-can-I-avoid-overfitting)

Answer¶

Methods for avoid overfittings are

  • Cross Validation

which generate more than one training and test dataset to avoid overfitting. For model choosing it is so effective

  • Early Stopping

Which stoph iteration before memorazing training dataset so we can predict more genarelized prediction on test dataset(more low bias, more high variance).

  • Pruning

Which remove some lowly effective nodes

  • Regularization

Which decrease some features coefficient(distribute them for generelization)(Ridge) or delete some of features which cause some overfitting(Lasso).
